  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in the shop when young folks try to figure out their place in the world. It's that moment when someone, especially a girl or a person of color, feels the weight of expectations about their ability to succeed in fields like engineering or coding, which can make them doubt themselves even when they're capable. I've worked with folks who've tried to learn electronics but got stuck because they were worried they wouldn't fit in or that they'd be judged as 'not smart enough.' It's real. And it's why I believe we should address it—not with big, sweeping policies but with small, consistent actions that make everyone feel seen and valued. For instance, in my shop, we've started having weekly 'skills sharing' sessions where people can talk about their struggles without judgment. That's helped build confidence and showed that it's okay to not know something right away. Addressing stereotype threat means creating environments where people feel safe to make mistakes and where their efforts are recognized, not just their outcomes. It's about fostering a culture where everyone knows they belong here, regardless of who they are or where they come from. That's not just good for STEM—it's good for the whole community. In Chicago, where we have so many diverse backgrounds, this kind of inclusive approach can really help bridge gaps and open doors for those who might otherwise feel left out.",
